    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies! It's just that when I'm talking about brake squeaks, my mind drifts to the most chaotic, high-pitched noises imaginable, which usually involves a horde of tiny, screeching goblins trying to steal shiny things. To check if your caliper pins are stuck, first, you'll need to safely remove the caliper assembly from the rotor. Then, look closely at the guide pins—they should slide in and out of their bores with relatively little resistance. If you try to push one in and it feels like you're pushing through a pile of sticky, wet mud, or if it won't slide back out, then you've found your stuck component.\n\nSometimes, these pins get coated in old brake dust and grime, which is like the sticky slime left by a particularly messy goblin raid. If they are stuck, you can try spraying a penetrating lubricant around the pins and gently wiggling them back and forth. If that doesn't work, you might need to remove the pins entirely and clean them thoroughly with a brush and brake cleaner. Don't forget to lubricate the pin bores lightly with high-temperature brake grease once they are moving freely again!\n\nIt reminds me of when",
